2.30	Joseph_Baptista_Gardens	Joseph Baptista Gardens	The Joseph Baptista Gardens, locally known as the Mazagaon Gardens, is a 1.5 acres (0.6 ha) park in south Mumbai in Mazagon. It lies atop a hill, the Bhandarwada Hill, and offers a panoramic view of the Mumbai harbour and the southern business district of the city. Beneath the gardens is a water reservoir, constructed by the second Municipal Commissioner of Mumbai, John Hay Grant (1877–1881) between 1880–1884. The gardens are located behind the Dockyard Road railway station, at an altitude of 32 metres (105 ft). Shortly after India's independence in 1947, the gardens, was named after Joseph Baptista, an Indian freedom activist.	
